# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: responsive-images
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] It’s been available across browsers since September 2023.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] The **`image-set()`** CSS functional notation is a method of letting the browser pick the most appropriate CSS image from a given set, primarily for high pixel density screens.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] Resolution and bandwidth differ by device and network access.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] The `image-set()` function delivers the most appropriate image resolution for a user's device, providing a set of image options — each with an associated resolution declaration — from which the browser picks the most appropriate for the device and settings.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] Resolution can be used as a proxy for filesize — a user agent on a slow mobile connection with a high-resolution screen may prefer to receive lower-resolution images rather than waiting for a higher resolution image to load.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] `image-set()` allows the author to provide options rather than determining what each individual user needs.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] The `<image>` can be any image type except for an image set.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] The `image-set()` function may not be nested inside another `image-set()` function.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] `<resolution>` units include `x` or `dppx`, for dots per pixel unit, `dpi`, for dots per inch, and `dpcm` for dots per centimeter.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] Every image within an `image-set()` must have a unique resolution.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] A valid MIME type string, for example "image/jpeg".
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] Browsers do not provide any special information on background images to assistive technology.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] This is important primarily for screen readers, as a screen reader will not announce its presence and therefore convey nothing to its users.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] If the image contains information critical to understanding the page's overall purpose, it is better to describe it semantically in the document.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] This example shows how to use `image-set()` to provide two alternative `background-image` options, chosen depending on the resolution needed: a normal version and a high-resolution version.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] In the next example the `type()` function is used to serve the image in AVIF and JPEG formats.
[src:responsive-images/css-image-set] If the browser supports avif, it will choose that version.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-currentsrc] The **`currentSrc`** read-only property of the `HTMLImageElement` interface indicates the URL of the image selected by the browser to load.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-currentsrc] A string indicating the full URL of the image currently selected by the browser to load.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-currentsrc] If the image uses the `srcset` attribute, `currentSrc` lets you determine which image from the set of provided images was selected by the browser.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-currentsrc] The property's value is unrelated to whether the image has successfully loaded or not.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-currentsrc] In this example, two different sizes are provided for an image of a clock.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-currentsrc] One is 200px wide and the other is 400px wide.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-currentsrc] The `sizes` attribute is provided to indicate that the image should be drawn at 50% of the document width if the viewport is under 400px wide; otherwise, the image is drawn at 90% width of the document.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] It’s been available across browsers since March 2016.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The **`sizes`** property of the `HTMLImageElement` interface allows you to specify the layout width of the image for each of a list of media queries, or `auto` for lazy-loaded images to allow the browser to automatically select an image to display based on the layout size of the element.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] This allows the browser to choose between different images specified in the element `srcset` to match different media conditions — even images with different orientations or aspect ratios.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The `sizes` property reflects the `<img>` element's `sizes` content attribute.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] It can only be present when `srcset` uses width descriptors.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] A string that can be the `auto` keyword (optionally followed by any number of *source sizes*), or one or more *source sizes*.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] See the `sizes` attribute in the HTML `<img>` reference for more information.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] This example demonstrates how the browser uses the `sizes` attribute to select an image from `srcset` based on the rendered width of the image at the current viewport width.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] It also allows you to see the effect of resizing the browser window on which image is loaded.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] In order to demonstrate the effect of lazy loading the images need to be initially hidden from the visual viewport, and then scrolled into view.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] This is achieved by having an outer `scroll-container` `<div>` that nests `spacer` and `demo-wrap` containers.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The image is contained inside the `demo-wrap` container, which is pushed out of the visual viewport by the height set on the `spacer` container.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The CSS and JavaScript are not shown (if you want to examine these, select "Play" to view the whole example in the interactive playground).
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The example is best viewed in its own window, so you can adjust the sizes fully, and the example is not constrained by its containing frame.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Resize the window — you should see the image change at the `sizes` attribute's media query break points.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Note that the selected image may be larger than the container width alone suggests.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Many displays, if not most, have a device pixel ratio (DPR) greater than one.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] In order to render a sharp image at the physical pixel density of the display, a browser will multiply the matched `sizes` hint by the DPR before selecting from `srcset`.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] For example, on a 2× display with a viewport of ~500px, the matched hint is `600px`, but the browser looks for a ~1200px image and selects `1200.png` as the closest available size and then scales it to fit in the available space.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] **Note:** As a result, some of the images in the `srcset` may not be reachable on a particular display at some break points, and this may be browser dependent.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The log provides information when a `load` event fires for the image, and when it intersects the visible viewport.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Note that the image is lazy-loaded, so the `load` event should be fired just before the image enters the viewport.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] This example demonstrates how setting the `sizes` value to `auto` affects the selection of the image to load from the `srcset` when `<img>` elements are lazy-loaded.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] It also allows you to see the effect of changing the size of a container on the loaded image.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The HTML is similar to that in the previous example, except that it defines three near-identical `<img>` elements, each with a `srcset` indicating 3 images that are `600px`, `400px`, and `200px` wide, and with a `sizes` value of `auto`.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] These are constrained within containers that are sized to select the different images.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Here we show the CSS classes that set the size of the different image containers.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The remaining CSS and the JavaScript that powers the slider, logging, and so on, are not shown (if you are interested in examining these, select "Play" to view the whole example in the interactive playground).
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Scroll the frame to display the three images.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The browser should have selected a different image for each based on the different width constraints.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] You can use the slider to modify the size of the container for the first image.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Note that the browser may or may not select a new image to display as the size of the container changes as implementations are not required to react to dynamic changes.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The log provides information when a `load` event fires for each image, and when an image intersects the visible viewport.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Note that the images are lazy-loaded, so the `load` event should be fired just before the image enters the viewport.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Also note that the `load` event also fires as you modify the container size for the first image, indicating when the browser has recalculated the layout (not necessarily that a new image has been loaded).
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] This example is a slightly more real-world case demonstrating how to select an image to fit a window width using source sizes.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] In this example, a blog-like layout is created, displaying some text and an image for which three size points are specified, depending on the width of the window.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Three versions of the image are also available, with their widths specified.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The browser takes all of this information and selects an image and width that best meets the specified values.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] How exactly the images are used may depend upon the browser and the pixel density of the user's display.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Buttons at the bottom of the example let you actually modify the `sizes` property slightly, switching the largest of the three widths for the image between 40em and 50em.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The JavaScript code handles the two buttons that let you toggle the third width option between 40em and 50em; this is done by handling the `click` event, using the JavaScript string `replace()` method to replace the relevant portion of the `sizes` string.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] The page is best viewed in its own window, so you can adjust the sizes fully, and the example is not constrained by its containing frame.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Set the width between `50em` `(800px)` and `60em` (`960px`) so that the last media query is selected.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-sizes] Then alternately press each of the buttons and note how the layout size of the image is changed.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-srcset] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-srcset] The **`srcset`** property of the `HTMLImageElement` interface identifies one or more *image candidate strings*, separated using commas (`,`), each specifying image resources to use under given circumstances.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-srcset] Each image candidate string contains an image URL and an optional width or pixel density descriptor that indicates the conditions under which that candidate should be used instead of the image specified by the `src` property.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-srcset] It reflects the `<img>` element's `srcset` content attribute.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-srcset] The `srcset` property, along with the `sizes` property, are a crucial component in designing responsive websites, as they can be used together to make pages that use appropriate images for the rendering situation.
[src:responsive-images/htmlimageelement-srcset] For more information about the syntax of the `srcset` attribute, see the HTML `<img>` reference.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] In this article, we'll learn about the concept of responsive images — images that work well on devices with widely differing screen sizes, resolutions, and other such features — and look at what tools HTML provides to help implement them.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] This helps to improve performance across different devices.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] A typical website may contain a header image and some content images below the header.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] The header image will likely span the whole of the width of the header, and the content image will fit somewhere inside the content column.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] However, issues arise when you start to view the site on a narrow screen device.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] The header below looks OK, but it's starting to take up a lot of the screen height for a mobile device.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] And at this size, it is difficult to see faces of the two people within the first content image.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] An improvement would be to display a cropped version of the image which displays the important details of the image when the site is viewed on a narrow screen.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] A second cropped image could be displayed for a medium-width screen device, like a tablet.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] The general problem whereby you want to serve different cropped images in that way, for various layouts, is commonly known as the **art direction problem**.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] In addition, there is no need to embed such large images on the page if it is being viewed on a mobile screen.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Doing so can waste bandwidth; in particular, mobile users don't want to waste bandwidth by downloading a large image intended for desktop users, when a small image would do for their device.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Conversely, a small raster image starts to look grainy when displayed larger than its original size (a raster image is a set number of pixels wide and a set number of pixels tall).
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Ideally, multiple resolutions would be made available to the user's web browser.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] The browser could then determine the optimal resolution to load based on the screen size of the user's device.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] This is called the **resolution switching problem**.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] To make things more complicated, some devices have high resolution screens that need larger images than you might expect to display nicely.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] This is essentially the same problem, but in a slightly different context.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] You might think that vector images would solve these problems, and they do to a certain degree — they are small in file size and scale well, and you should use them wherever possible.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] However, they aren't suitable for all image types.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Vector images are great for simple graphics, patterns, interface elements, etc., but it starts to get very complex to create a vector-based image with the kind of detail that you'd find in say, a photo.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Raster image formats such as JPEGs are more suited to the kind of images we see in the above example.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] This kind of problem didn't exist when the web first existed, in the early to mid 90s — back then the only devices in existence to browse the Web were desktops and laptops, so browser engineers and spec writers didn't even think to implement solutions.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] In this section, we'll look at the two problems illustrated above and show how to solve them using HTML's responsive image features.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] You should note that we will be focusing on `<img>` elements for this section, as seen in the content area of the example above — the image in the site header is only for decoration, and therefore implemented using CSS background images.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] CSS arguably has better tools for responsive design than HTML, and we'll talk about those in a future CSS module.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] So, what is the problem that we want to solve with resolution switching?
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] We want to display identical image content, just larger or smaller depending on the device — this is the situation we have with the second content image in our example.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] We can however use two attributes — `srcset` and `sizes` — to provide several additional source images along with hints to help the browser pick the right one.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] The `srcset` and `sizes` attributes look complicated, but they're not too hard to understand if you format them as shown above, with a different part of the attribute value on each line.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Each value contains a comma-separated list, and each part of those lists is made up of three sub-parts.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] The image's **intrinsic width in pixels** (`480w`) — note that this uses the `w` unit, not `px` as you might expect.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] An image's intrinsic size is its real size, which can be found by inspecting the image file on your computer (for example, on a Mac you can select the image in Finder and press Cmd + I to bring up the info screen).
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Work out which media condition in the `sizes` list is the first one to be true.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Look at the slot size given to that media query.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Load the image referenced in the `srcset` list that has the same size as the slot.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] If there isn't an exact match for the display size, the browser will choose the first image that is bigger than the chosen slot size and scale it down to fit.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] At this point, if a supporting browser with a viewport width of 480px loads the page, the `(width <= 600px)` media condition will be true, and so the browser chooses the `480px` slot.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] The `elva-fairy-480w.jpg` will be loaded, as its inherent width (`480w`) is closest to the slot size.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] The 800px picture is 128KB on disk, whereas the 480px version is only 63KB — a saving of 65KB.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Now, imagine if this was a page that had many pictures on it.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Using this technique could save mobile users a lot of bandwidth.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] To see which images were loaded, you can use Firefox DevTools's Network Monitor tab or Chrome DevTools's Network panel.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] For Chrome, you may also want to disable cache to prevent it from picking already downloaded images.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Older browsers that don't support these features will just ignore them.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Instead, those browsers will go ahead and load the image referenced in the `src` attribute as normal.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Suppose you have an image that will be rendered at the same real-world size on displays that have different screen resolutions.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] You can provide a better user experience on high resolution displays by serving a higher resolution version of the image.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] To achieve this you can allow the browser to choose an appropriate resolution image by using `srcset` with x-descriptors and without `sizes` — a somewhat easier syntax!
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Note that even though the image is always displayed with the same size, on higher resolution displays you get to see more details.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] In this case, `sizes` is not needed — the browser works out what resolution the display is that it is being shown on, and serves the most appropriate image referenced in the `srcset`.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] The 640px image is 93KB, whereas the 320px image is only 39KB.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] To recap, the **art direction problem** involves wanting to change the image displayed to suit different image display sizes.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] For example, a web page includes a large landscape shot with a person in the middle when viewed on a desktop browser.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] When viewed on a mobile browser, that same image is shrunk down, making the person in the image very small and hard to see.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] It would probably be better to show a smaller, portrait image on mobile, which zooms in on the person.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] The `<picture>` element allows us to implement just this kind of solution.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Like `<video>` and `<audio>`, the `<picture>` element is a wrapper containing several `<source>` elements that provide different sources for the browser to choose from, followed by the all-important `<img>` element.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] When the browser starts to load a page, it starts to download (preload) any images before the main parser has started to load and interpret the page's CSS and JavaScript.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] That mechanism is useful in general for reducing page load times, but it is not helpful for responsive images — hence the need to implement solutions like `srcset`.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] For example, you couldn't load the `<img>` element, then detect the viewport width with JavaScript, and then dynamically change the source image to a smaller one if desired.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] By then, the original image would already have been loaded, and you would load the small image as well, which is even worse in responsive image terms.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] In this exercise, we're expecting you to be brave and do it alone, mostly.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] We want you to implement your own suitable art-directed narrow screen/wide screenshot using `<picture>`, and a resolution switching example that uses `srcset`.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Find a nice wide screen landscape image with some kind of detail contained in it somewhere.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Create a web-sized version of it using a graphics editor, then crop it to show a smaller part that zooms in on the detail, and create a second image (about 480px wide is good for this).
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Use the `<picture>` element to implement an art direction picture switcher!
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Create multiple image files of different sizes, each showing the same picture.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] Use `srcset`/`sizes` to create a resolution switcher example, either to serve the same size image at different resolutions depending on the device resolution or to serve different image sizes depending on the viewport widths.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-images] That's a wrap for responsive images — we hope you enjoyed playing with these new techniques.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] , on a computer screen (left) and on a mobile phone screen (right).
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] The elements rearrange themselves into a more mobile friendly layout.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Responsive web design became more important as users of mobile devices came to account for the majority of website visitors.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] In 2015, for instance, Google announced Mobilegeddon and started to boost the page ranking of mobile-friendly sites when searching from a mobile device.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Responsive web design is an example of user interface plasticity.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Luke Wroblewski has summarized some of the responsive and mobile design challenges and created a catalog of multi-device layout patterns.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] He suggested that, compared with a simple responsive web design approach, device experience or RESS (responsive web design with server-side components) approaches can provide a user experience that is better optimized for mobile devices.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Server-side CSS generator implementation of stylesheet languages like Sass can be part of such an approach.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Google has recommended responsive design for smartphone websites over other approaches.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Although many publishers have implemented responsive designs, one challenge for responsive design adoption was that some banner advertisements and videos were not fluid.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] However, search advertising and (banner) display advertising came to support specific device platform targeting and different advertisement size formats for desktop, smartphone, and basic mobile devices.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Different landing page URLs have been used for different platforms, or Ajax has been used to display different advertisement variants on a page.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] CSS tables permitted hybrid fixed and fluid layouts.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] There have been many ways of validating and testing responsive web designs, ranging from mobile site validators and mobile emulators to simultaneous testing tools like Adobe Edge Inspect.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] The Chrome, Firefox and Safari browsers and developer tools have offered responsive design viewport resizing tools, as do third parties.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] The W3C specification of HTML+ stated that websites have to be rendered according to the user preferences.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] The customization of web page layout was lacking however.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Many web developers resorted to ordinary HTML tables as a way to customize the layout and bring some basic responsiveness to their websites at the same time.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Limited browser capabilities meant that for Internet Explorer, the layout could adapt dynamically in the browser whereas, for Netscape, the page had to be reloaded from the server when resized.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Cameron Adams created a demonstration in 2004.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] By 2008, a number of related terms such as "flexible", "liquid", "fluid", and "elastic" were being used to describe layouts.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] CSS3 media queries were almost ready for prime time in late 2008/early 2009.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Ethan Marcotte coined the term *responsive web design*—and defined it to mean fluid grid / flexible images / media queries—in a May 2010 article in *A List Apart*.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] He described the theory and practice of responsive web design in his brief 2011 book titled *Responsive Web Design*.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Responsive design was listed as #2 in Top Web Design Trends for 2012 by .net magazine after progressive enhancement at #1.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] Mashable called 2013 the Year of Responsive Web Design.
[src:responsive-images/responsive-web-design] User interface plasticity is the capacity of a user interface to withstand variations of both the system's physical characteristics and the environment while preserving usability.
